87; 18 ) &#1608;&#1582;&#1575;&#1605;&#1587;&#1607;&#1575; &#1604;&#1593;&#1604;&#1607;&#1605; &#1575;&#1578;&#1582;&#1584;&#1608;&#1607;&#1575; &#1605;&#1581;&#1575;&#1585;&#1610;&#1576; &#1604;&#1589;&#1604;&#1608;&#1575;&#1578;&#1607;&#1605; &#1608;&#1591;&#1575;&#1593;&#1575;&#1578;&#1607;&#1605; &#1608;&#1610;&#1587;&#1580;&#1583;&#1608;&#1606; &#1573;&#1604;&#1610;&#1607;&#1575; &#1604;&#1575; &#1604;&#1607;&#1575; &#1603;&#1605;&#1575; &#1571;&#1606;&#1575; &#1606;&#1587;&#1580;&#1583; &#1573;&#1604;&#1609; &#1575;&#1604;&#1602;&#1576;&#1604;&#1577; &#1604;&#1575; &#1604;&#1604;&#1602;&#1576;&#1604;&#1577; &#1608;&#1604;&#1605;&#1575; &#1575;&#1587;&#1578;&#1605;&#1585;&#1578; &#1607;&#1584;&#1607; &#1575;&#1604;&#1581;&#1575;&#1604;&#1577; &#1592;&#1606; &#1575;&#1604;&#1580;&#1607;&#1575;&#1604; &#1605;&#1606; &#1575;&#1604;&#1602;&#1608;&#1605; &#1571;&#1606;&#1607; &#1610;&#1580;&#1576; &#1593;&#1576;&#1575;&#1583;&#1578;&#1607;&#1575; &#1608;&#1587;&#1575;&#1583;&#1587;&#1607;&#1575; &#1604;&#1593;&#1604;&#1607;&#1605; &#1603;&#1575;&#1606;&#1608;&#1575; &#1605;&#1606; &#1575;&#1604;&#1605;&#1580;&#1587;&#1605;&#1577; &#1601;&#1575;&#1593;&#1578;&#1602;&#1583;&#1608;&#1575; &#1580;&#1608;&#1575;&#1586; &#1581;&#1604;&#1608;&#1604; &#1575;&#1604;&#1585;&#1576; &#1601;&#1610;&#1607;&#1575; &#1601;&#1593;&#1576;&#1583;&#1608;&#1607;&#1575; &#1593;&#1604;&#1609; &#1607;&#1584;&#1575; &#1575;&#1604;&#1578;&#1571;&#1608;&#1610;&#1604; &#1601;&#1607;&#1584;&#1607; &#1607;&#1610; &#1575;&#1604;&#1608;&#1580;&#1608;&#1607; &#1575;&#1604;&#1578;&#1610; &#1610;&#1605;&#1603;&#1606; &#1581;&#1605;&#1604; &#1607;&#1584;&#1607; &#1575;&#1604;&#1605;&#1602;&#1575;&#1604;&#1577; &#1593;&#1604;&#1610;&#1607;&#1575; &#1581;&#1578; &#1609; &#1604;&#1610;&#1589;&#1610;&#1585; &#1576;&#1581;&#1610;&#1579; &#1610;&#1593;&#1604;&#1605; &#1576;&#1591;&#1604;&#1575;&#1606;&#1607; &#1576;&#1590;&#1585;&#1608;&#1585;&#1577; &#1575;&#1604;&#1593;&#1602;&#1604;</div>    <P>
Al-Razi has provided six explanations as to what the objective of these people might be:    <P>
<ul><li> <b>The first</b>, regarding a people who believe in Allah and the Angels, and believe that Allah and the Angels have beautiful forms, and that the Angels are veiled behind the heaven and inaccessible, so they make statues of them in the form and shape they believed those Angels to be, and then they give <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> to them, seeking nearness to Allaah and those Angels, so their reason here was that they believed in resemblance between the statues they created and the Angels.    <P>
<li> <b>The second</b>, that many people saw the changes and events taking place in the world connected to changes in the positions of the stars, and the nearness and distance to the sun to the polar axis determines the variation in the seasons and the likes. Then they observed the positions of all of the stars and believed that good fortune and bad fortune in the world is tied to how they appear in relation to the people (their births and the likes). So when they believed this, they exaggerated in venerating these stars, and some of them believed that these entities are obligatory in their existence, and they created the universe, and others believed they are created by the greatest deity, but that they in turn created this universe. So the first group treated them as creators and deities and the second group treated them as <a href='../tags/intermediaries.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>intermediaries</font></a> (wasaa'it) between Allaah and mankind, and thus there is no harm in worshipping them and humbling to them. Then when they saw that the stars are not visible to them for most of the time (except at night), they set up idols for them, and directed <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> to them, but in reality intending <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> of those planetary bodies. Then when time passed over them, after the passing of generations, they abolished the mention of the stars, and worshipped just those idols, and they in reality are worshippers of the stars.    <P>
<li> <b>The third</b>, a people who used to specify certain times, through a period of lengthy years, such as a thousand, or two-thousand, and claimed that whoever took up a talisman in a particular form in that particular time would benefit in specific ways, such as in being happy and being fertile and the likes. Thus, they venerated these talismans and exaggerated until it became <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a>, and then when a lengthy time passed by, their descendants forgot the initial reason, and they became occupied with worshipping them, ignorant of the original matter.    <P>
<li> <b>The fifth</b>, perhaps they took their niches (mihrabs) as their places of <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> and their acts of obedience, and prostration towards them, but not for them, just like we prostrate towards the qiblah, not for the qiblah. And then the situation continued like this, perhaps the ignorants from the people thought that it was obligatory to <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> them.    <P>
<li> <b>The sixth</b>, perhaps they used to be Mujassimah who beleived that Allaah indwells in their statues and so they worshipped them upon this ta'wil (interpretation).   </ul>    <P>
As for <b>the fourth</b>, he said regarding it:    <P>
<div class='arabic' align='right'>&#1608;&#1585;&#1575;&#1576;&#1593;&#1607;&#1575; &#1571;&#1606;&#1607; &#1605;&#1578;&#1609; &#1605;&#1575;&#1578; &#1605;&#1606;&#1607;&#1605; &#1585;&#1580;&#1604; &#1603;&#1576;&#1610;&#1585; &#1610;&#1593;&#1578;&#1602;&#1583;&#1608;&#1606; &#1601;&#1610;&#1607; &#1571;&#1606;&#1607; &#1605;&#1580;&#1575;&#1576; &#1575;&#1604;&#1583;&#1593;&#1608;&#1577; &#1608;&#1605;&#1602;&#1576;&#1608;&#1604; &#1575;&#1604;&#1588;&#1601;&#1575;&#1593;&#1577; &#1593;&#1606;&#1583; &#1575;&#1604;&#1604;&#1607; &#1578;&#1593;&#1575;&#1604;&#1609; &#1575;&#1578;&#1582;&#1584;&#1608;&#1575; &#1589;&#1606;&#1605;&#1575;&#1611; &#1593;&#1604;&#1609; &#1589;&#1608;&#1585;&#1578;&#1607; &#1610;&#1593;&#1576;&#1583;&#1608;&#1606;&#1607; &#1593;&#1604;&#1609; &#1575;&#1593;&#1578;&#1602;&#1575;&#1583; &#1571;&#1606; &#1584;&#1604;&#1603; &#1575;&#1604;&#1573;&#1606;&#1587;&#1575;&#1606; &#1610;&#1603;&#1608;&#1606; &#1588;&#1601;&#1610;&#1593;&#1575;&#1611; &#1604;&#1607;&#1605; &#1610;&#1608;&#1605; &#1575;&#1604;&#1602;&#1610;&#1575;&#1605;&#1577; &#1593;&#1606;&#1583; &#1575;&#1604;&#1604;&#1607; &#1578;&#1593;&#1575;&#1604;&#1609; &#1593;&#1604;&#1609; &#1605;&#1575; &#1571;&#1582;&#1576;&#1585; &#1575;&#1604;&#1604;&#1607; &#1578;&#1593;&#1575;&#1604;&#1609; &#1593;&#1606;&#1607;&#1605; &#1576;&#1607;&#1584;&#1607; &#1575;&#1604;&#1605;&#1602;&#1575;&#1604;&#1577; &#1601;&#1610; &#1602;&#1608;&#1604;&#1607; &#1607;&#1614;&#1572;&#1615;&#1604;&#1575;&#1569; &#1588;&#1615;&#1601;&#1614;&#1593;&#1614;&#1575;&#1572;&#1615;&#1606;&#1614;&#1575; &#1593;&#1616;&#1606;&#1583;&#1614; &#1575;&#1604;&#1604;&#1617;&#1614;&#1607;&#1616; ( &#1610;&#1608;&#1606;&#1587; 18 )</div>    <P>
<blockquote class='quote'><img src='../images/quote-start.gif'>And the fourth of them, that when a senior man died amongst them, and they believed that his <a href='../tags/supplication.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>supplication</font></a> is answered and his <a href='../tags/intercession.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>intercession</font></a> is accepted with Allaah, the Exalted, they took an idol in his form, and worshipped it upon the belief that that man will be an intercessor for them with Allaah on the Day of Judgement, upon what Allaah, the Exalted, has informed abuot them in this statement in His saying, "<b>[They say], these are our intercessors with Allaah</b>" (10:18).</blockquote>    <P>
As has preceded, and as is clear from this entire section, these people do not actually intend <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> of the idols in and of themselves, and their <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> is not actually directed to the idols, they are in fact worshipping the righteous dead man from whom they are hoping to solicit <a href='../tags/intercession.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>intercession</font></a>. However, there may be people who forgot the original intent and ended up being devoted to idols, as al-Razi has indicated with some of those people, but certainly most of those who <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> other than Allaah simply use representations, be they idols, statues,  pictures, photos and graves and tombs as mere focal points for <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> which they are really directing to the angels, prophets or righteous. And this <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> includes <a href='../tags/dua.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>du'a</font></a> (<a href='../tags/supplication.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>supplication</font></a>) and the types of fear, hope, aspiration, humility and the likes which are due only for Allaah, which often accompany <a href='../tags/dua.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>du'a</font></a> (<a href='../tags/supplication.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>supplication</font></a>) - and al-Razi clearly holds that <a href='../tags/dua.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>du'a</font></a> is from the greatest of <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a>, is from its essence and is inextricably tied to those states and feelings of the heart which are in themselves <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> (<a href=../index0b41.html?asmag >see this article</a>).    <P>
<div class='sidebar'><b>Summary</b>    <P>
In summary of this article, al-Razi has indicated the action of those people who solicit the <a href='../tags/intercession.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>intercession</font></a> of the righteous dead, using a statue or idol as the focal point. And the objection of the saint worshippers of today is to say that they do not <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> idols, hence are not committing <a href='../tags/shirk.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>shirk</font></a>, and nor do they believe these in the power of benefit or harm for any besides Allaah. The answer to them is the very answer of al-Razi in <a href=../index7248.html?fgnbc>this article</a> and <a href=../index6578.html?pqwqp>this article</a> and from what he said was, in addressing this very matter:    <P>
<blockquote>And know that the Kuffar posed a question to this speech [i.e. concerning the <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> of inanimate things], so they said: We do not <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> these idols due to a belief that they are deities that can harm or benefit. We <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> them because they are representations of individuals who are near ones to Allaah. So we <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> them (the representations) for the reason that those senior ones (al-akaabir) become intercessors for us with Allaah. So Allaah the Most High replied saying: "<b>Have they taken others as intercessors besides Allah? Say: "Even if they have power over nothing whatever and have no intelligence?</b>" </blockquote>    <P>
And also:    <P>
<blockquote>And it is possible for it to be said that the intelligent being does not <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> an idol in the sense that it is mere wood or stone, but they <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> it due to their belief that these [things] are representations of the stars, or representations of the heavenly spirits, or representations of the Prophets and righteous (dead) who have passed away. And their intent behind worshipping them (the statues, idols, representations) is to direct those acts of <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> to those things [the stars, heavenly spirits, prophets, righteous] for which they have made these representations as [tangible] forms for them. </blockquote>    <P>
And also:    <P>
<blockquote>And the fourth of them: That they made these idols and statues upon the form and shape of their Prophets and senior [righteous] ones (al-akaabir), and they claimed that when they occupied themselves with the <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> of these statues, then those senior [righteous] ones (al-akaabir) will be intercessors for them with Allaah. <b>And the equivalent of this in our time is the occupation of many of the creation with the veneration of the graves of the senior [righteous] ones, upon the belief that when they venerate their graves, then they (the deceased) will become intercessors for them with Allaah</b>.</blockquote>    <P>
Thus, the idol, or statue, or picture, or grave, or tomb, is merely the focal point - just like a Muslim turns towards the qiblah, but is not worshipping the qiblah (ka'bah) - then likewise with these people who seek <a href='../tags/intercession.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>intercession</font></a>, they are worshipping the righteous dead by supplicating to them directly and seeking istighaathah, and asking them directly to intercede for them, or to relieve them of calamity and the likes, and they will sacrifice an animal at the grave, or direct such actions of the heart such as fear and hope towards that righteous dead person, which is only befitting for Allaah - and in all of that it is the tomb, or grave which is merely a focal point. No one of sound intelligence worships a statue, or idol, or a grave, or a tomb thinking it has power over good and evil or harm and benefit - as al-Razi has stated a few times as we have quoted from him in this series of articles - rather, they affirm only Allaah has power over harm and benefit, but they solicit <a href='../tags/intercession.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>intercession</font></a> through the righteous dead, directing what is no doubt <a href='../tags/worship.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>worship</font></a> to them, hoping that they might receive their <a href='../tags/intercession.html' class='tagLink'><font class='tagLink'>intercession</font></a>.    <P>
These meanings outlined in these statements of al-Razi (d. 606H) are no different to what is found in the writings of Ibn Taymiyyah (d. 728H) and of Ibn Abdul-Wahhab (d. 1175H).</div>    <P>
